"1259–1316","1163–1228":"1163–1228","1175–1234":"1175–1234","1264":"1264","Abt 1259":"circa 1259","1175":"1175","1263":"1263","1163":"1163","1271":"1271","Abt 1239":"circa 1239","1228":"1228","1316":"1316","1239":"1239","1205":"1205","1259":"1259","1204":"1204","1214":"1214","1269":"1269","1234":"1234","1219":"1219","1207":"1207","Baildon, Yorkshire, England":"Baildon, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Allerton, Yorkshire, England":"Allerton, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Thurston, Suffolk, England":"Thurston, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1214–":"1214–Deceased","1204–Female":"1204–Deceased","1205–1207":"1205–1207","1205–1264":"1205–1264","1207–1271":"1207–1271","1214–Female":"1214–Deceased","1219–1263":"1219–1263","1239–1269":"1239–1269","1259–1316":"1259–1316","1163–1228":"1163–1228","1175–1234":"1175–1234","1264":"1264","Abt 1259":"about 1259","1175":"1175","1263":"1263","1163":"1163","1271":"1271","Abt 1239":"about 1239","1228":"1228","1316":"1316","1239":"1239","1205":"1205","1259":"1259","1204":"1204","1214":"1214","1269":"1269","1234":"1234","1219":"1219","1207":"1207","Baildon, Yorkshire, England":"Baildon, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Allerton, Yorkshire, England":"Allerton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Thurston, Suffolk, England":"Thurston, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: possibly a metonymic occupational name for a fisherman, from <i>orfe</i>, a species of freshwater fish. Alternatively, a habitational name from Urff near Kassel, formerly Orpha."],"variants":[{"name":"Orff","meanings":["German: variant of   Orf  ."]}]},{"name":"Allerton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from any of several places so called. Allerton on Merseyside, Chapel Allerton in Yorkshire, and others in Yorkshire were named in Old English as <i>alra tūn</i> ‘settlement by the alders’. One in Somerset (<i>Alwarditone</i> in Domesday Book) is ‘Ælfweard's settlement’; one in Yorkshire (Allerton Mauleverer, <i>Alvertone</i> in Domesday Book) is ‘Ælfhere's settlement’.","(Suffolk): probably a variant of   Alderton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Alderton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of a number of places called Alderton. Those in Suffolk and Shropshire (<i>Alretuna</i> in Domesday Book) are named with Old English <i>alor</i> + <i>tūn</i>, meaning ‘the settlement by the alders’. Those in Gloucestershire, Northamptonshire, and Wiltshire are named with the Old English personal name <i>Ealdhere</i>, meaning ‘settlement associated with Ealdhere’. The one in Essex contains a different personal name, probably the woman's name Æthelwaru. In England, the surname is most common in East Anglia, making the places in Suffolk and Essex the most likely sources."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Lewis   or respelling of   Lou  , as borne by the impresario  Lew Grade  (  1906–98 , originally  Louis Winogradsky )."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Blount","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Midlands): variant of   Blunt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Blunt","meanings":["English: nickname for someone with fair hair or a light complexion, from Old French <i>blund</i>, <i>blond</i> (from Latin <i>blondus</i>) ‘blond, fair, yellow-haired’, used also of complexion."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes le Blount of Allerton was born in 1214, in Allerton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, William II le Blount - 5th Baron Ixworth, was 51 and her mother, Cecilia de Vere, was 40. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with William de Criketot I. She died in Baildon, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1214–":"1214–Surnud","1204–Female":"1204–Surnud","1205–1207":"1205–1207","1205–1264":"1205–1264","1207–1271":"1207–1271","1214–Female":"1214–Surnud","1219–1263":"1219–1263","1239–1269":"1239–1269","1259–1316":"1259–1316","1163–1228":"1163–1228","1175–1234":"1175–1234","1264":"1264","Abt 1259":"umbes 1259","1175":"1175","1263":"1263","1163":"1163","1271":"1271","Abt 1239":"umbes 1239","1228":"1228","1316":"1316","1239":"1239","1205":"1205","1259":"1259","1204":"1204","1214":"1214","1269":"1269","1234":"1234","1219":"1219","1207":"1207","Baildon, Yorkshire, England":"Baildon, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Allerton, Yorkshire, England":"Allerton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Thurston, Suffolk, England":"Thurston, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1214–":"1214–Kuollut","1204–Female":"1204–Kuollut","1205–1207":"1205–1207","1205–1264":"1205–1264","1207–1271":"1207–1271","1214–Female":"1214–Kuollut","1219–1263":"1219–1263","1239–1269":"1239–1269","1259–1316":"1259–1316","1163–1228":"1163–1228","